<p>A philosophy professor has a question about teaching that I think will resonate with many readers.<span id="more-55264"></span></p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><span style="color: #bab8b8;">.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_55265" style="width: 610px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-55265" class=" wp-image-55265" src="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/kristof-kat-portrait-of-him-detail-1024x690.jpg" alt="" width="600" height="404" srcset="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/kristof-kat-portrait-of-him-detail-1024x690.jpg 1024w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/kristof-kat-portrait-of-him-detail-300x202.jpg 300w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/kristof-kat-portrait-of-him-detail-768x517.jpg 768w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/kristof-kat-portrait-of-him-detail-400x269.jpg 400w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/kristof-kat-portrait-of-him-detail.jpg 1253w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /><p id="caption-attachment-55265" class="wp-caption-text">[&#8220;Portrait of Him&#8221; (detail) by Kat Kristof]</p></div>This professor teaches many lower- and mid-level philosophy courses in ethics and epistemology, but sometimes other subfields as well, and they have a problem they&#8217;re hoping some of you can help with.</p>
<p>They write:</p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><em>I would like to be able to teach my students the views, or the versions of views, most likely to have a shot at being correct. Often, these are relatively contemporary formulations, developed in light of the various problems with previous versions of the views. Yet I have found it difficult to find presentations of them that are written in a language or style comprehensible to non-experts, and that do not presume familiarity with the history of the inquiry. I&#8217;m curious about why this is the situation we&#8217;re in, but more importantly, I am curious about what other instructors with pedagogical aims similar to mine do. Are there texts, teaching resources, tools, or strategies they would recommend?</em></p>
<p>Your suggestions are encouraged.</p>
<p>In the background of this question is another one about the aims of lower- and mid-level philosophy courses, and perhaps an implicit criticism of common teaching practices in philosophy, which readers are also welcome to take up.</p><p>The post <a href="https://dailynous.com/2025/10/09/teachable-and-state-of-the-art/">Teachable and State of the Art</a> first appeared on <a href="https://dailynous.com">Daily Nous</a>.</p>